	(24726,544,'wpcf-short-description','Speculative open-source research based on the design fiction that we can control our endogenous DMT, a powerful psychedelic compound produced in the human body.'),
	(24727,544,'wpcf-long-description','DMT, or Dimethyltryptamine, is one of the most powerful psychedelics, temporarily changing the neural pathways of our brain so that we become immersed in a raw data-sphere of imagery, sensations and encounters. It’s also abundant throughout the plant and animal kingdoms, including within us. DMT is the only known endogenous psychedelic, meaning we produce it naturally in the human body. However, outside of the body it’s highly illegal, classified as a Schedule One drug. This restriction on research has meant that our knowledge of this fascinating compound is incredibly limited and largely speculative. DIY DMT is a speculative new open-source program dedicated to advancing our knowledge of endogenous DMT and its potential benefits, based on the design fiction that we can manipulate its behavior in our bodies. In particular, the program encourages the translation of this research into tangible prospects, providing the most innovative proposals with access to top facilities around the world. The very first series of projects to emerge from this program are now on exhibit. This striking trio of bio-designs is represented by a multimedia installation of physical prototypes, an iPad application supplying background research and applicant stories, and an introductory film to the program. \r\n\r\nThe first project focuses on the way DMT creates its own unique connections in the brain, enabling us to process our world without the hierarchy or filtering of our senses. In order to harness this mechanism, Leo Mackenzie is bio-hacking the brain’s dormant Pineal Gland, rewiring it as the body’s DMT regulator. He predicts that the redesigned gland will begin to restore DMT to its original purpose as our inner third eye, opening up new possibilities for intuitive learning, problem-solving and creativity. The second project is inspired by an ancient Amazonian plant medicine, Ayahuasca (“The Grandmother\"), in which DMT is the psycho-active ingredient. Ayahuasca is sacred to these communities for its enabling the formation of strong bonds between people and to the earth. But in the first ever known case, Pauline Shakti, who has come to be known as The Grandmother’s Daughter, was born with it already in her veins. Pauline is developing her mother’s controversial research by distilling the Ayahuasca vine into a pregnancy supplement, to reconnect future generations to their roots from within the womb. Finally, Dr. Joan Grace wishes to refine DMT’s healing powers by integrating two of its significant behaviors: the release of suppressed, often painful material in the brain, and DMT\'s common uplifting effect (due to its close chemical relation to the hormone Serotonin). She proposes that re-balancing our natural DMT levels could help us better understand and treat depression on a deep molecular level, and is developing a device that gently facilitates this process through the breath.\r\n\r\nDIY DMT invites you to consider not the possibility of these designs in our future, but rather the greater mystery at the core of this psychedelic renaissance: why is DMT within us in the first place?'),
