	(25861,560,'wpcf-short-description','An informative project about fracking that aims to inform the viewer, but at the same time satirize the process of looking for information by using the metaphor of the maze.'),
	(25862,560,'wpcf-long-description','True and false, good and bad, right and wrong are ambiguous concepts. So much so that people’s minds can be easily manipulated by pressure groups. What I try to do is to present both sides of a hotly debated question - in this case the acceptability of fracking.  My aim is to not only show how ambiguous a question can be, but also educate the public in the process. At the same time, the confusing and maze-like structure of the project is a satire of the modern idea of transparency, where it is used more to hide information in a mess of facts and a lack of oversight instead of bringing greater clarity. Hence the \"infomaze,\" or a maze of information.\r\n\r\nI hope to make public opinion stronger by being better informed. To keep the attention of the reader I use humor, knowing very well how manipulative humor itself can be (the danger of irony is that it can get taken seriously). Poker-faced, I present both sides of the issue, while at the same time making use of the same tropes pro-frackers and anti-frackers use to advance their argument. My greatest hope is that this project inspires the viewer to embark on their own \"infomaze\" - to search deeper for nuanced information in order to better advance their own point of view.\r\n\r\nThe project itself is a large, interactive infographic. Combining the visual languages of illustration and animation, the \"infomaze\" allows the viewer to navigate through the large maze, interacting with it and discovering the different stages of fracking: exploration (the act of finding a promising location), leasing, prospecting, financing, production and, finally, the environmental and economical impacts of the process. However, the path itself has many branches, some providing more information, and some derailing the viewer into a completely different path of inquiry, eventually leading them off the maze and somewhere else.'),
