	(664,1,'2014-04-18 21:02:54','2014-04-19 02:02:54','Currently developing and writing a non-fiction theatre piece, \"Jack From Above.\" He has colloborated with such artists as Pete Townshend and Barry Levinson. As a theatre director, he has worked at many theatres directing new plays, revivals, and performance pieces. As a filmmaker, his short films and documentaries have premiered at The Sundance Film Festival and on PBS. His writing has appeared in Bomb, Interview, Paper, and The Evening Standard in London as well as the photography book, \"Backstage: Broadway behind the Curtain\"(Abrams). He helped develop the curriculum for Journeys in Film, a middle school syllabus that teaches cross-cultural understanding through foreign film. Ethan attended Oberlin College and The Drama Studio, London. Yaddo Residencies: 2008,2010.','Ethan Silverman','','publish','closed','closed','','ethan-silverman','','','2014-04-19 13:28:40','2014-04-19 18:28:40','',0,'http://dev.mfadt.com/2014/?post_type=faculty&#038;p=664',0,'faculty','',0),
	(665,1,'2014-04-18 21:02:59','2014-04-19 02:02:59','Colleen Macklin is a game designer, an Associate Professor in the school of Art, Media and Technology at Parsons The New School for Design and founder and co-director of PETLab (Prototyping Education and Technology Lab), a lab that develops games for experimental learning and social engagement. PETLab projects include disaster preparedness games and sports with the Red Cross, the urban activist game Re:Activism and the physical/fiscal sport Budgetball. PETLab has also published game design curricula for the Boys and Girls Club and via the website <a href=\"http://activategames.org/\" target=\"_blank\">activategames.org</a>. She is a member of the game design collective Local No. 12, best known for their collectible card game, the Metagame and The Leisure Collective, a group exploring games and experimental narrative. Her work has been shown at Come Out and Play, UCLA Art|Sci Center, The Whitney Museum for American Art and Creative Time. BFA Media Arts Pratt Institute, MA International Affairs, The New School, graduate studies in Computer Science, CUNY.','Colleen Macklin','','publish','closed','closed','','colleen-macklin','','','2014-04-19 13:26:42','2014-04-19 18:26:42','',0,'http://dev.mfadt.com/2014/?post_type=faculty&#038;p=665',0,'faculty','',0),
	(666,1,'2014-04-18 21:03:05','2014-04-19 02:03:05','Chris Prentice is an independent writer, educator and researcher/strategist working new product and service development. From Epson to MacArthur \"Genius\", Elizabeth Streb, her work consistently helps individuals and corporations communicate and implement innovative visions. She is included on U.S. patents and has received international press for ideas ranging from electronic system design to conceptual urban interventions. Chris is also a poet, choreographer, performing artist and recovering arts administrator and funder. She holds a BA in Dance and English Literature from Washington University in St. Louis and an MFA in Creative Writing from Sarah Lawrence College. She is currently on the thesis faculty for the Design &amp; Technology MFA program at Parsons, The New School for Design.','Christine Prentice-Popken','','publish','closed','closed','','christine-prentice-popken','','','2014-04-19 13:26:05','2014-04-19 18:26:05','',0,'http://dev.mfadt.com/2014/?post_type=faculty&#038;p=666',0,'faculty','',0),
	(667,1,'2014-04-18 21:03:14','2014-04-19 02:03:14','Career has encompassed academia, business and the non-profit realm. Technical director for NCEA, an international educational non-profit funded by the Ford Foundation. Product design team leader at a technology start-up that developed AI software. Professor of film studies and literature at UCLA, Rutgers and Fordham Universities. Research fellowships from Fulbright, the American Council of Learned Societies and the governments of Spain, the U.S. and Argentina; published book on the Spanish filmmaker Pedro Almodovar. Communications consultant and editor, worked with Oxford University Press, Prentice Hall, KPMG, Sony, Hansol and Ernst and Young. Producer of documentary film, Half a Soulja. One of founders of thesis writing program in Parsons MFA in Design and Technology; teaching writing at Parsons since 2001.','Barbara Morris','','publish','closed','closed','','barbara-morris','','','2014-04-19 13:25:11','2014-04-19 18:25:11','',0,'http://dev.mfadt.com/2014/?post_type=faculty&#038;p=667',0,'faculty','',0),
	(668,1,'2014-04-18 21:03:19','2014-04-19 02:03:19','<a href=\"https://www.landornet.com/Secure/Landor/People/?S=9H03569\" target=\"_blank\">Anthony Deen</a> is the Creative Director for Environments and Experiences at Landor NY. In his eighteen years of practice, Anthony was a Senior Architect for The Rockwell Group, Senior Design Director and Hospitality Studio Director for The Phillips Group Architecture, and Vice President of Design and Development for the Virgin Megastores in North America.\r\n\r\nIn these positions his clients have included Apple, Barclays, British Airways, Central Park, FAO Schwarz, jetBlue, Macy’s, Mercedes Benz, ToyRUs, W Hotels, and the World Trade Center. Notable projects include the re-launch of FAO Schwarz’s flagship stores in New York and Las Vegas, the renovation of British Airways premium lounges at JFK’s Terminal 7, and the interior of jetBlue’s Terminal 5 also at JFK Airport.\r\n\r\nA graduate of the Cooper Union, Anthony co-founded the Design + Technology program at Parsons School of Design with Sven Travis, and is an Associate Professor and teaches graduate Thesis Studio. Professionally trained as an architect, Anthony is a LEED Green Associate, an associate member of the American Institute of Architects and the Illuminating Engineering Society, and a professional member of the Society of Environmental Graphic Designers.','Anthony Deen','','publish','closed','closed','','anthony-deen','','','2014-04-19 13:23:58','2014-04-19 18:23:58','',0,'http://dev.mfadt.com/2014/?post_type=faculty&#038;p=668',0,'faculty','',0),
	(669,1,'2014-04-18 21:03:24','2014-04-19 02:03:24','Andrew Zornoza is a novelist and photographer; he is the author of the photo-prose novel \'Where I Stay.\' Born in Houston, Texas, and educated at Princeton University, he has taught at The New School University and Gotham Writers\' Workshop, as well as in Parsons Design &amp; Technology MFA program. His short fiction and essays have appeared in magazines such as BOMB, The Poetry Foundation, Gastronomica, Sleepingfish, Confrontation, Porcupine Literary Arts, CapGun, and Matter Magazine, among others. Long, long ago he contributed to the documentation of distributed systems, Java Application servers, and the first primitive applications for cell phones. He is now an editor of the critical contemporary arts and literature journal H.O.W. He currently lives in New York City.','Andrew Zornoza','','publish','closed','closed','','andrew-zornoza','','','2014-05-06 20:38:27','2014-05-07 01:38:27','',0,'http://dev.mfadt.com/2014/?post_type=faculty&#038;p=669',0,'faculty','',0),
